### For Loop in C#

The `for` loop is ideal when you know the exact number of iterations in advance.

### Syntax

```csharp
for (initializer; condition; iterator)
{
    // Code to repeat
}
```

### Basic Example

```csharp
for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++)
{
    Console.WriteLine($"Iteration: {i}");
}
```

### Loop Components

| Part | Description | Example |
|------|-------------|---------|
| Initializer | Runs once before loop starts | `int i = 0;` |
| Condition | Checked before each iteration | `i < 5;` |
| Iterator | Runs after each iteration | `i++` |

### Multiple Variables

```csharp
for (int i = 0, j = 10; i < j; i++, j--)
{
    Console.WriteLine($"i={i}, j={j}");
}
```

### Looping Through Arrays

```csharp
int[] numbers = { 10, 20, 30, 40, 50 };
for (int i = 0; i < numbers.Length; i++)
{
    Console.WriteLine($"Index {i}: {numbers[i]}");
}
```

### Optional Parts

All three parts of the for loop are optional:

```csharp
// Infinite loop
for (;;)
{
    // Runs forever unless break
}

// Only initializer and condition
int i = 0;
for (; i < 10;)
{
    Console.WriteLine(i);
    i++;
}
```

### Nested For Loops

```csharp
for (int row = 0; row < 3; row++)
{
    for (int col = 0; col < 3; col++)
    {
        Console.Write($"({row},{col}) ");
    }
    Console.WriteLine();
}
```

### for vs while

| Aspect | for | while |
|--------|-----|-------|
| Best for | Known iteration count | Unknown iteration count |
| Compactness | All loop logic in one line | Condition separated from init/iterator |
| Readability | Counting loops | Condition-based loops |

> **Key Point:** The for loop is best for iterating a known number of times. The initializer runs once, the condition is checked before each iteration, and the iterator runs after each iteration's code block.

### Range-Based Loops

Use `foreach` for collections, but for index access, `for` is still needed:

```csharp
for (int i = 0; i < list.Count; i++)
{
    if (i % 2 == 0)
        Console.WriteLine(list[i]);
}

codeExample:
using System;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Multiplication Table (5):");
        for (int i = 1; i <= 10; i++)
        {
            Console.WriteLine($"5 x {i} = {5 * i}");
        }

        Console.WriteLine("\nCountdown:");
        for (int i = 10; i >= 0; i--)
        {
            Console.Write($"{i} ");
        }
    }
}
